

                         SEDIT v1.10 User Manual
                     CP/M 2.2 Full-Screen Text Editor

                    ================================


    1.  INTRODUCTION

    SEDIT is a full-screen text editor for CP/M 2.2 systems equipped
    with a VT100-compatible terminal.  It provides WordStar-style
    control key commands, block operations, find/replace, syntax
    highlighting for assembly language, and support for editing files
    larger than available memory using disk-backed virtual buffers.

    SEDIT requires an Intel 8080 or compatible processor, a minimum of
    9 KB free TPA (Transient Program Area), and a VT100/ANSI terminal
    or emulator supporting cursor addressing and SGR attributes.


    2.  STARTING SEDIT

    From the CP/M command prompt:

        A>SEDIT                     Start with empty buffer
        A>SEDIT MYFILE.TXT          Open MYFILE.TXT for editing

    If the named file exists, it is loaded into the edit buffer.  If
    it does not exist, an empty buffer is created with that filename
    assigned.

    When a file is too large to fit entirely in the TPA, SEDIT
    automatically switches to virtual buffer mode.  The status line
    displays "Large file: using virtual buffer..." and the file is
    split across disk-backed temporary files.  Editing proceeds
    normally; page-up and page-down across buffer boundaries trigger
    automatic merge-split operations.


    3.  SCREEN LAYOUT

    SEDIT uses a 24-row by 80-column display (132-column mode is
    also available via the ESC menu).

        Row  1    Information bar: filename, line count, cursor
                  position (row:col), file length, insert/overwrite
                  mode indicator
        Row  2    Tab ruler (: marks every 4 columns)
        Rows 3-22 Edit area (20 lines of text)
                  Columns 1-5: line number gutter
                  Columns 6-78: text area
        Row 23    Separator bar (=== line)
        Row 24    Status/message line (prompts and messages)

    Line numbers in the gutter are 1-based and track the actual file
    line number.  The text area displays up to 73 characters per line
    in 80-column mode (125 in 132-column mode).  Lines may contain up
    to 255 characters; horizontal scrolling is automatic.


    4.  KEY COMMANDS

    SEDIT uses WordStar-compatible control key sequences.  The ^
    symbol indicates the Ctrl key (e.g. ^E means Ctrl-E).  Two-key
    sequences are shown as ^K,B meaning press Ctrl-K, release, then
    press B.

    4.1  Cursor Movement

        ^E          Cursor up one line
        ^X          Cursor down one line
        ^S          Cursor left one character
        ^D          Cursor right one character
        ^A          Move to previous word
        ^F          Move to next word
        ^R          Page up (scroll up 20 lines)
        ^C          Page down (scroll down 20 lines)
        ^W          Scroll up one line
        ^Z          Scroll down one line
        ^Q,S        Jump to beginning of line (Home)
        ^Q,D        Jump to end of line (End)
        ^Q,R        Jump to beginning of file
        ^Q,C        Jump to end of file

        Arrow keys, Home, End, PgUp, PgDn, Insert, and Delete keys
        are also recognized via VT100 escape sequences.

    4.2  Editing

        ^V          Toggle insert/overwrite mode (default: insert)
        ^I          Insert a tab character
        ^M          Insert a new line (carriage return)
        ^N          Insert a new line (alternate binding)

    In insert mode, typed characters are inserted at the cursor and
    text to the right shifts over.  In overwrite mode, typed
    characters replace the character at the cursor position.  The
    current mode is shown on the information bar as "I" (insert) or
    "OVR" (overwrite).

    4.3  Deletion

        ^H          Delete character to the left (Backspace)
        ^G          Delete character to the right
        Del         Delete character to the right
        ^Y          Delete entire current line
        ^K,W        Delete word to the right

    When deleting at a line boundary, the current line and the next
    line are joined.  If the resulting line would exceed 255
    characters, the join is refused with an error message.

    4.4  Block Operations

        ^K,B        Block mark: set start, then set end, then clear
        ^K,C        Copy marked block to clipboard
        ^K,D        Delete marked block
        ^K,P        Paste clipboard at cursor position

    Block marking is a three-state toggle:
      - First ^K,B sets the block start at the cursor ("Mark start.")
      - Second ^K,B sets the block end at the cursor ("Mark end.")
      - Third ^K,B clears all marks ("Mark clear.")

    The marked region is highlighted during full screen redraws.
    The clipboard holds up to 2048 bytes.

    4.5  Find

        ^Q,F        Find text (prompts for search string)
        ^L          Find next (repeat last search)
        F1          Find next (repeat last search)

    The search string may be up to 64 characters.  Search is case-
    insensitive and starts from the current cursor position.  If the
    text is not found forward, the search does not wrap.  The status
    line displays "Found." or "Not found." as appropriate.

    4.6  File Operations

        ^K,S        Save file
        ^K,X        Exit editor (prompts to save if modified)
        ^K,Q        Quit editor (prompts to save if modified)
        F2          Save file

    When saving, the original file is renamed to .BAK before the new
    version is written.  If the file has no name yet, you are
    prompted to enter one.

    When exiting with unsaved changes, SEDIT prompts:

        Save changes? (Y/N/Esc)

        Y   Save the file, then exit
        N   Discard changes and exit
        Esc Cancel and return to editing


    5.  ESC MENU

    Press the Escape key (or F4) to open the menu overlay.  Select
    an option by pressing the corresponding number (1-9), the first
    letter of the option, or by using arrow keys and Enter.  Press
    Escape to close the menu without selecting.

        1. Open        Open a file (prompts for filename)
        2. Save        Save current file
        3. Save As     Save to a new filename
        4. Find        Search for text
        5. Go To       Jump to a line number
        6. Help        Display key reference screen
        7. About       Show version information
        8. 80/132 col  Toggle 80/132 column display mode
        9. Exit        Quit the editor

    The "Go To" option prompts for a decimal line number and
    positions the cursor at that line.

    The 80/132 column toggle sends VT100 DECCOLM escape sequences.
    The screen is cleared on mode change (this is normal VT100
    behavior).  In 132-column mode, the text area expands to 125
    visible columns.


    6.  FUNCTION KEYS

        F1          Find next (same as ^L)
        F2          Save file (same as ^K,S)
        F3          Block mark (same as ^K,B)
        F4          Open ESC menu


    7.  SYNTAX HIGHLIGHTING

    SEDIT provides syntax highlighting for 8080/Z80 assembly language
    source files.  Highlighting is enabled automatically when the
    file extension is .MAC, .ASM, or .INC.

    Token colors:

        Labels (column 1)      Yellow
        Opcodes/directives     Green
        Registers              Cyan
        Numbers                Magenta
        Strings                Magenta
        Comments (;)           Dim

    Syntax highlighting is a compile-time option controlled by the
    SYNHI equate.  Set SYNHI=1 for assembly highlighting or SYNHI=0
    to disable it (smaller binary).  Because SEDIT.INC is inlined
    into each source file by CPMFMT.PY, this equate must be edited
    directly in SESCREEN.MAC and SESYNTAX.MAC.

    Color output is controlled by the COLOR equate in SESCREEN.MAC.
    Set COLOR=0 for monochrome terminals.


    8.  KEY BINDING CUSTOMIZATION

    SEDIT reads an optional key binding file named SEDIT.KEY from the
    current disk at startup.  This file allows reassigning control
    key actions.

    File format (plain text, one binding per line):

        $ This is a comment line
        CTRL 5 WRDPV
        CTRL 6 WRDNX
        CTRL 18 PGUP

    Each CTRL line maps a control character (0-31) to an action name.
    Action names correspond to the internal action codes:

        CURUP   CURDN   CURLT   CURRT   WRDPV   WRDNX
        PGUP    PGDN    SCRUP   SCRDN   LINST   LINEN
        FTOP    FEND    DELLF   DELRT   DELWD   DELLN
        INSTB   INSNL   TOGIN   LITNX   FNDNX   FSAVE
        FOPEN   FEXIT   BLKMK   BLKCP   BLKDL   BLKPS
        MENU

    Action names are case-insensitive.


    9.  VIRTUAL BUFFER MODE

    When a file is too large to fit in the TPA, SEDIT splits it into
    three regions:

        BEFORE temp file    Lines above the in-memory buffer
        Gap buffer in TPA   Currently visible/editable portion
        AFTER temp file     Lines below the in-memory buffer

    Temporary files are created on the current disk:

        SEDIT00B.TMP        BEFORE temp
        SEDIT00A.TMP        AFTER temp
        SEDIT00M.TMP        MERGE temp (used during repositioning)

    Navigation (page up/down, go-to-line) across buffer boundaries
    triggers an automatic merge-split operation.  The status line
    shows "Virtual buffer: repositioning..." during this process.

    On save, all three regions are written to the output file in
    sequence.  Temporary files are deleted on exit.

    Note: Virtual buffer mode requires sufficient free disk space for
    the temporary files, which together hold a complete copy of the
    file being edited.


    10. FILE SIZE LIMITS

    Maximum file size depends on available TPA and disk space:

      - Without virtual buffer: limited to TPA size minus ~15 KB for
        SEDIT code and data (typically 40-45 KB on a 64K system)
      - With virtual buffer: limited by available disk space for the
        temporary files
      - Maximum line length: 255 characters
      - Maximum clipboard size: 2048 bytes
      - Maximum search string: 64 characters

    SEDIT requires a minimum of 9 KB free TPA.  If insufficient
    memory is available, the message "Insufficient memory" is
    displayed and the editor exits.


    11. BACKUP FILES

    When saving, SEDIT renames the original file to have a .BAK
    extension before writing the new version.  If a .BAK file already
    exists, it is deleted first.  This provides one level of backup.


    12. STATUS MESSAGES

    Common messages displayed on the status line (row 24):

        Please wait, loading file...
        File loaded.
        File saved.
        Saving file, please wait...
        Large file: using virtual buffer...
        Virtual buffer: repositioning...
        Disk full or write error! Press any key.
        File is too big.
        Insufficient memory.
        Mark start. / Mark end. / Mark clear.
        No block. / Block copied / Block del.
        Pasted. / Clip empty.
        Found. / Not found.
        Save changes? (Y/N/Esc)
        Line NNN is wider than 255 characters.


    13. TERMINAL REQUIREMENTS

    SEDIT requires a VT100/ANSI compatible terminal supporting:

      - Cursor addressing:  ESC [ row ; col H
      - Erase screen:       ESC [ 2 J
      - Erase to end of line: ESC [ K
      - Show/hide cursor:   ESC [ ? 25 h / ESC [ ? 25 l
      - SGR attributes:     ESC [ Ps m  (0=reset, 1=bold, 2=dim,
                            7=reverse, 31-37=foreground colors)
      - DECCOLM (optional): ESC [ ? 3 h / ESC [ ? 3 l
                            (for 80/132 column toggle)

    The terminal must support at least 80 columns by 24 rows.

    Input escape sequences recognized:

        ESC [ A/B/C/D       Arrow keys (up/down/right/left)
        ESC [ H / ESC [ F   Home / End (xterm)
        ESC [ 1~ / ESC [ 4~ Home / End (VT220)
        ESC [ 2~            Insert
        ESC [ 3~            Delete
        ESC [ 5~ / ESC [ 6~ Page Up / Page Down
        ESC O P/Q/R/S       F1 / F2 / F3 / F4


    14. EXITING

    To exit SEDIT, use any of:

        ^K,X        Exit with save prompt
        ^K,Q        Quit with save prompt
        ESC -> 9    Menu exit

    If the file has been modified, you are prompted to save.  SEDIT
    returns to CP/M via a warm boot.


    15. UTILITY PROGRAMS

    The following standalone utilities are included with SEDIT.  Each
    sends VT100/ANSI escape sequences to the terminal and returns to
    CP/M.

    COL80.COM       Set terminal to 80-column mode.

        A>COL80

        Sends the VT100 DECCOLM reset sequence (ESC [ ? 3 l) to
        switch the terminal to 80-column display mode.

    COL132.COM      Set terminal to 132-column mode.

        A>COL132

        Sends the VT100 DECCOLM set sequence (ESC [ ? 3 h) to
        switch the terminal to 132-column display mode.

    CLS.COM         Clear screen and home cursor.

        A>CLS

        Sends the VT100 erase-screen sequence (ESC [ 2 J) followed
        by the cursor-home sequence (ESC [ H).

    GETWIDTH.COM    Detect and display terminal width.

        A>GETWIDTH
        Terminal width: 80 columns

        Queries the terminal using VT100 Device Status Report and
        displays the detected column count.


                         ================================
